{{!
Custom override of upstream JavaSpring/javaBuilder.mustache (openapi-generator v7.21.0,
modules/openapi-generator/src/main/resources/JavaSpring/javaBuilder.mustache).

Near-identical to advanced/javaBuilder.mustache (sibling). Kept as a separate file because
the openapi-generator-maven-plugin's <templateDirectory> is per-execution: the simple-variant
execution looks here, the advanced execution looks in advanced/. When changing the staged-builder
emission shape, edit both files in lockstep.

NOTE: Do NOT use Mustache tag syntax inside this comment block. The samskivert Mustache engine
parses section tags even inside comment blocks, so any unclosed section tag in this comment would
corrupt the template parse tree and cause a MustacheParseException.

Three intentional differences vs advanced/javaBuilder.mustache, all caused by the simple variant
using broader type mappings that flatten some allOf-inheritance schemas into non-extending classes:

Difference 1: the x-optional-parent-vars blocks (IBuild methods, Impl fields, Impl override
methods) are wrapped in a parent-section guard here. For flat-inlined classes (no Java extends),
the parent vars are already in the class's own vars list — emitting them again from
x-optional-parent-vars would produce duplicate fields and methods.

Difference 2: the optional setters in IBuild/Impl use x-optional-own-vars (pre-computed by
EnrichSpec) instead of the template-level vars-inverted-required iteration when a staged chain
exists. In the simple variant, flat-inlined schemas may have inherited-and-required fields appear
as own vars with required=false in the generator context (because the property was declared
optional in an ancestor). Using x-optional-own-vars (which applies mergedRequired logic) avoids
emitting optional setters for fields that are actually required by the child schema. The guard
uses x-has-staged-chain (a boolean flag set by EnrichSpec alongside x-staged-chain) rather than
iterating x-staged-chain, to avoid a cartesian product emission with x-optional-own-vars. When
no staged chain exists, falls back to vars-inverted-required (no duplication risk). nullableAnnotation
is stored in the extension entries (same as x-optional-parent-vars) rather than using the partial.

Difference 3: the x-needs-child-ctor no-parent path in build() uses vars-iteration instead of
x-all-ctor-args. EnrichSpec computes x-all-ctor-args in own-props-first order for child schemas,
but the pojo ctor for flat-inlined classes (no Java parent, x-needs-child-ctor) uses the
generator vars declaration order (parent-vars-first, own-vars-last). Using vars directly keeps
build() args in sync with the ctor params for those flat classes. The final fallback path (no
parent, no ctor flags) still uses x-all-ctor-args — consistent with the advanced template — since
discriminator union types (which reach that path) have an empty x-all-ctor-args and a no-args ctor.

Wholesale replacement, not an incremental diff: upstream emits a flat single-Builder where every
setter returns the same Builder type and build() is unconditionally callable. That gives no
compile-time required-field enforcement.

This override emits a staged nested Builder. Per-required-field stage interfaces are laid out
according to vendorExtensions.x-staged-chain (computed by the in-module Groovy preprocessor at
src/build/groovy/EnrichSpec.groovy). Each stage method returns the next stage; only the terminal
IBuild exposes build() and any optional setters. Skipping a required field is a return-type
mismatch caught by javac.

When bumping openapi-generator: re-fetch upstream javaBuilder.mustache at the new version. If
upstream changed shape significantly (e.g. switched to records, changed deserialization
annotations), re-evaluate whether our staged-builder design still composes. Update the version
reference.
}}
